#HelloWorld. 
 
Welcome to multidisciplinary creator @gabrielle_rosenstein’s (Gabrielle Rosenstein) sci-femme fantasy: “a universe of super-curvy, hyper-girlie, strong and cool chrome characters” that spans digital and physical realms. 
 
Gabrielle’s hyper-stylized depictions of the female form serve as “a metaphor for the hidden power that lies within seemingly unassuming cuteness and the multifaceted essence of femme energy.” 
 
“My designs inherently reflect my queer identity — a love letter to women, a crush, an alter ego, an extension of my very being. My 3D characters started off as bare-bodied silhouettes, acting as the garments, but the progression of world-building led to customizing outfits and accessories fit for their future-cute galaxy.” 
 
The organic evolution of this universe has surpassed digital bounds, culminating in the launch of Gabrielle’s FW23 collection, “Charm” — bringing her 3D sci-femme universe to life through wearable accessories including bags, key charms and charm bracelets. 
 
“Through my collection, I invite everyone to join in the escapism and unlock their authentic sci-dentities and bring a tangible piece of life the journey back to the physi world.” 
 
Video and music by @gabrielle_rosenstein

“I am incredibly proud of who I am and where I come from. As a descendent of storytellers, I’ve felt a responsibility from a young age to preserve and pass on stories of survivance and celebration.” —Diné (Navajo) poet, educator and playwright @kinsalehues (Kinsale Drake)
 
“Indigenous peoples are often framed in a negative light due to stereotype, underrepresentation, miseducation and tragic narratives, but my work seeks to find joy, futurities and the beauty of our survivance,” says Kinsale, whose first book, “The Sky Was Once A Dark Blanket,” a collection about Native music, won the 2023 National Poetry Series.
 
Kinsale is also the director of NDN Girls Book Club. “We platform Indigenous authors, support Native youth in their creative endeavors nationwide, provide free writing workshops, provide books for tribal libraries and reading circles and send out Native literature for free. 
 
Collectivity is powerful; supporting one another makes a world of difference. My work is ultimately for my community and to make them proud.”
 
Photos by @kinsalehues and @ericaelan

No running with scissors! ✂️✂️ 
 
Happy Halloween from @theshihtzusophie (Tobi and Sophie), two siblings who love to dress up in costumes, because there’s always a tasty treat at the end. #WeeklyFluff 
 
Video by @theshihtzusophie 
Music by @bobsinclar

Belgian ceramic artist and fashion designer @naomigilon (Naomi Gilon) creates contemporary chimeras — unique anthropomorphic hybrid objects that mix fantasy, terror and sublimity.

“All my pieces are handmade, with no molding involved, using either stoneware or porcelain. Bags and other accessories, or body sculptures, are wearable — that's the goal. They go beyond the static contemplation of ‘art.’”

Naomi has developed a signature obsession in her work. “These monstrous hands — with long claws, neither human nor animal, something beyond us — draw inspiration from car customization, manga, science fiction, horror films, the image of the rock star and myths. However, my reflections are more related to society, human behavior, scientific advances, crises, etc.

Myths are full of monsters. Monsters reflect our fears, and horror seeks to evoke fear and insecurity within each of us.”

Photos and videos by @naomigilon

“I present myself to the world as the boy of dreams.” —Makeup artist and designer @lucasmakeup (Lucas da Costa Reis) 
 
Lucas’ powerful makeup looks — with their signature omnipresent splashes, distinctive competing colors and slicked-back hair painted to match — provide a form of therapy, giving him strength to overcome anxiety and depression. 
 
“I not only do makeup, but I also give it life. I love creating makeup based on feelings, whether it’s sad, powerful, hurt or even happy, to convey what I’m feeling that day. My makeup is much more than just paint on my face, it’s a new version of me.” 
 
Video by @lucasmakeup 
Music by Kausak

@brentfaiyaz (Brent Faiyaz) is full of surprises.

Before headlining the @onemusicfest in Atlanta this weekend, the R&B artist dropped a brand-new surprise album, which, like Brent, lives up to its name: “Larger than Life.”

And while he may be a Maryland native, he’s showing us #10Things from his home away from home ahead of tonight’s show. 

1. 📍 Atlanta for @onemusicfest 🍑
2. Showtime decisions…
3. Necessary accessories.
4. @nuwo.world fit check ✅🔥
5. Pre-show hype up with @bobbyybanks 
6. It’s mint. 🫖
7. Pit stop at @originalfani 
8. When @timbaland calls about the collab.
9. Larger. Than. Life.
10. Final sound check. See you at the show.

Let’s play ball! ⚾️ 👏

Last night the @mlb World Series got underway, as the @rangers matched up against the @dbacks. Taking in the action was 21-year-old content creator and college student @katiefeeneyy (Katie Feeney), who documented her five favorite moments — from batting practice on the field to snacks in the bleachers.

@tayakun (Taya Lindsey) needs no excuse to put together a special look. 
 
“I love dressing up, whether it’s for going to work, the gas station or an anime convention. I love expressing myself through the way I dress — it could be with makeup, accessories or just the whole outfit. It shows people that I’m going to dress the way I want, whether they like it or not.” 
 
Taya’s love of cosplay and anime helps them build on outfits they’ve previously worn. “I think about what can make this one better, what can I add to this piece and just do a lot of mixing and matching. 
 
I get a lot of people telling me they wish they could dress the way I do but are too scared of being judged. Who cares what others think? If you like it, do it.” 
 
Photo by @tayakun

“Sometimes I think I’m not goated, but then I take a step back and I’m, like, wait — I’m goated.” —Musician EKKSTACY (@ekkstacy)
 
EKKSTACY first started making beats on his grandma’s computer when he was in his mid-teens. “Some not cool things happened to me that led me to start singing and recording music when I was 16. My song ‘I walk this earth all by myself’ changed my life very quickly. I went from working a 9-to-5 in Vancouver to being able to tour and live in LA,” says EKKSTACY, whose sound embraces “elements of indie, punk and shoegaze and a few other things.”
 
“I’m not trying to do anything or force anything, I’m the most impulsive person that I know. I just do what I want in the moment. It works well for me. I’ve always been this way. There’s no plan for me.
 
I like bringing people together. I like seeing everyone having fun and seeing everyone happy. When I do a show and there are 1,000 kids having fun, I did that.”

Video of @ekkstacy by @jason_nocito_studio 
Music by @ekkstacy
